      Barstool
   =20
 =20

One way to think about it is that if you are a gambling company, and it is =
2020 and sports gambling is  becoming broadly legal in the US, you will wan=
t to market sports gambling broadly to potential customers, and the best wa=
y to do that might be to team up with a popular sports media brand. Name yo=
ur sports gambling site after the sports media brand, and at the top of eve=
ry article on the media brand=E2=80=99s website have a little call to actio=
n like =E2=80=9CI see you are reading about the Mets, would you like to pla=
ce a wager on the Mets?=E2=80=9D You are fundamentally a=C2=A0gambling=C2=
=A0company, which is still a bit suspicious and seedy to some sports fans; =
you will get more customers and trust and=C2=A0goodwill from a=C2=A0sports=
=C2=A0company.
So, when sports gambling is becoming broadly legal in the US, you strike a =
marketing partnership=C2=A0with the very biggest and best sports media bran=
d you can get. Which will not be=C2=A0that=C2=A0big or=C2=A0that=C2=A0good.=
 You=E2=80=99re not going to get ESPN. It=E2=80=99s early days for broadly =
accepted sports gambling, it=E2=80=99s still a little edgy, and the best yo=
u will do is teaming up with kind of an edgy sports media brand. Barstool S=
ports, for instance, the bro-y and controversial site that appeals particul=
arly to young men.=C2=A0And you will pay it a large amount of money for a l=
icensing deal where you get to name your sports gambling site Barstool Spor=
tsbook and advertise it on Barstool=E2=80=99s media properties.
And you=E2=80=99ll do that for a few years, and legal sports gambling will =
continue to take off and become more widely acceptable and normal in the US=
,=C2=A0and then one day you=E2=80=99ll look around and say =E2=80=9Cwait ac=
tually now we can get ESPN.=E2=80=9D And so you will. You will=C2=A0enter a=
 licensing deal with ESPN, where you call your sports gambling site ESPN Be=
ts and advertise it on ESPN=E2=80=99s media properties.=C2=A0
And it would be confusing to do both simultaneously, so you end your licens=
ing deal with Barstool. And you reach an agreement with Barstool not to lic=
ense their name to any=C2=A0other=C2=A0gambling sites, so that there=E2=80=
=99s not a Barstool Bets out there to confuse your customers. And you renam=
e Barstool Sportsbook as ESPN Bets and get a wider audience for your sports=
 gambling. And if you paid Barstool $550 million for roughly three years of=
 marketing, that=C2=A0is maybe a bit high, but legal sports gambling in the=
 US was kind of a gold rush and maybe that number wasn=E2=80=99t crazy.
I don=E2=80=99t know, that=E2=80=99s one interpretation. The other interpre=
tation =E2=80=94=C2=A0the one that is more literally accurate =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0is that Dave Portnoy sold Barstool to Penn Entertainment Inc. for $550 m=
illion in 2020
  [1]
=C2=A0and then   bought it back yesterday=C2=A0for zero dollars:

Walt Disney Co.=E2=80=99s ESPN has signed a long-term exclusive agreement w=
ith casino operator Penn Entertainment Inc., licensing its brand for sports=
 betting and deepening the media giant=E2=80=99s ties to the growing online=
 gambling business.
Penn will have the 10-year right to use the ESPN Bet name in the US, the co=
mpany said in a statement Tuesday. Penn will rebrand its Barstool sportsboo=
k with ESPN starting this fall. ...
Penn also said Tuesday it=E2=80=99s selling all of its Barstool Sports Inc.=
 subsidiary to David Portnoy, who founded the sports and pop culture media =
company, in exchange for a non-compete and other agreements. Penn has the r=
ight to get half of the proceeds received by Portnoy in any subsequent sale=
 of Barstool. =E2=80=A6
Penn will make cash payments totaling $1.5 billion over the 10-year term an=
d grant ESPN $500 million of warrants to purchase Penn shares. ESPN will ha=
ve the right to designate one, non-voting board observer at Penn. The casin=
o company can extend the term for another 10 years by mutual agreement. Pen=
n said the deal could generate between $500 million and $1 billion in annua=
l earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization. ...
Starting in 2020, Penn bought Barstool in two transactions totaling more th=
an $550 million, part of the growing convergence of sports, media and gambl=
ing. The casino operator launched sportsbooks under the Barstool brand name=
 and said it helped the company reach a younger audience.
But the affiliation with Barstool also brought unwanted attention. On an ea=
rnings call in February of last year, Penn Chief Executive Officer Jay Snow=
den urged investors to be patient after articles on the website Insider det=
ailed sexual misconduct claims against Portnoy. The accusations led gamblin=
g regulators in some states to review Penn=E2=80=99s business. Earlier this=
 year, Barstool paid a $250,000 fine after regulators in Ohio found it brok=
e rules on advertising near a college campus and targeting customers under =
21.
In a video posted Tuesday on X, formerly known as Twitter, Portnoy said Bar=
stool and Penn =E2=80=9Cunderestimated just how tough it is for myself and =
Barstool to operate in a regulated world.=E2=80=9D He suggested that Barsto=
ol had been denied state gambling licenses because of him, and that he has =
no plans to sell Barstool sports again.
=E2=80=9CFor the first time in forever, we don=E2=80=99t need to watch what=
 we say, how we talk, what we do,=E2=80=9D Portnoy said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=
=99s back to the pirate ship.=E2=80=9D

And:
"Every time we did something, it was one step forward, two steps back," Por=
tnoy said in his video announcement on Tuesday. "We got denied licenses bec=
ause of me. You name it. So the regulated industry probably not the best pl=
ace for Barstool Sports and the type of content we make."
Look, as a trade, I am always going to love a founder selling high at the p=
eak of the cycle=C2=A0and then buying back low when valuations have collaps=
ed. (=E2=80=9CThe Wag trade,=E2=80=9D I have   sometimes called it, after t=
he dog-walking startup that extracted a bunch of money out of SoftBank Grou=
p Corp. when SoftBank was particularly enthused about, you know, throwing h=
undreds of millions of dollars at dog-walking startups, and then bought Sof=
tBank out cheap when that enthusiasm waned.) And I suppose if this is your =
plan, then it helps to (1) sell high, (2) continue running your startup as =
a division of the buyer and (3) be=C2=A0controversial and bad at it, so the=
 value goes down and the buyer feels forced to sell. Crafty!
  [2]

But =E2=80=9CDave Portnoy sold Barstool high at the peak of legalized sport=
s gambling in 2020, and then bought it back low when the bubble popped in 2=
023,=E2=80=9D does not seem quite right? I would not exactly say that Penn =
got what it paid for, with Barstool, but on the other hand  Penn=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9Cinteractive=E2=80=9D segment =E2=80=94=C2=A0consisting largely tho=
ugh not exclusively of its =E2=80=9Conline sports betting and casino app ca=
lled Barstool Sportsbook and Casino=E2=80=9D and its in-casino Barstool-bra=
nded retail sportsbooks =E2=80=94=C2=A0went from $121 million in revenue in=
 2020 to  $663 million in 2022, and was  up another 66% year-over-year in t=
he first half of 2023, for a run rate of almost $1 billion. =E2=80=9CBarsto=
ol has been a great partner and we are thankful to Dave Portnoy, Erika Ayer=
s, Dan Katz and their team for helping to rapidly scale our digital footpri=
nt across 16 jurisdictions in the U.S. and introducing their audience to ou=
r retail and digital products,=E2=80=9D said Penn in  announcing yesterday=
=E2=80=99s deal. Could Penn have added $500 million of annual sports gambli=
ng revenue=C2=A0without=C2=A0the marketing partnership? Could it have added=
=C2=A0more, without the public-relations and licensing problems that Barsto=
ol brought? Quite possibly! There really was a pretty big sports-gambling g=
old rush, and it does look like=C2=A0Penn spent lavishly and imprecisely to=
 get in on it.
But basically Penn paid $550 million to Barstool to get into online sports =
gambling with a popular brand, and amortized that cost over about three yea=
rs, or call it $180 million a year. And now it is paying ESPN $2 billion fo=
r a 10-year licensing agreement, or $200 million a year. Portnoy didn=E2=80=
=99t exactly sell Barstool at the peak and buy at the bottom: He sold Barst=
ool at the point when it made sense for Penn to partner with Barstool, and =
bought it back at the point when it made sense for Penn to partner=C2=A0wit=
h Disney.
One assumes that Penn would have preferred to sell Barstool back to Portnoy=
 for some price higher than zero, but:
=09It didn=E2=80=99t make sense for them to keep it,=09It was perhaps too c=
ontroversial for most other media or gaming companies, and=C2=A0=09Presumab=
ly any buyer would have to come to terms with Portnoy for it to make sense.

So I guess Portnoy was the only bidder? I dunno, I just Googled =E2=80=9CDa=
ve Portnoy enemies=E2=80=9D and got  this list that he tweeted last year be=
ginning with Henry Blodget, and if I were Penn I would have called Blodget =
(a wealthy media mogul!)=C2=A0and said =E2=80=9Chey you can have Dave Portn=
oy for $10,000=E2=80=9D just to see if I could spark a bidding war. It is p=
ossible though that Portnoy=E2=80=99s non-compete promises are worth more t=
o Penn than a buyer would pay.
Also Penn gets 50% of the proceeds if Portnoy sells. He =E2=80=9Chas no pla=
ns to sell Barstool Sports again,=E2=80=9D and why would he? He sold it for=
 $550 million and got it back for free; selling it again would just be gree=
dy. Once you=E2=80=99ve cashed out $550 million and kept the business, it=
=C2=A0can be a lifestyle business. I assume that Penn=E2=80=99s 50% is just=
=C2=A0schmuck insurance.
  [3]
=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s embarrassing enough to buy it from Portnoy for $550 mill=
ion and then sell it back to him=C2=A0for $0, but it would be much worse if=
 he turned around and sold it to someone else for $550 million again.

