   =20
      WeWork
   =20
 =20

Elsewhere in, uh, controversial founders who sold high and then rode their =
startups=C2=A0down to zero, I have always had kind of a soft spot for WeWor=
k Inc.=E2=80=99s business model. WeWork did many absurd things, which I lov=
ingly documented, but the idea=C2=A0seems fine? Companies want to outsource=
 real-estate management, lots of people work for smaller startup-y companie=
s that want flexible office arrangements, and particularly in this new post=
-pandemic world of remote work it makes sense for office-space management t=
o be more flexible and outsourced and pooled. I feel like if WeWork didn=E2=
=80=99t exist and you started it now, people would say =E2=80=9Coh that mak=
es a lot of sense.=E2=80=9D
But WeWork does exist, and=C2=A0it does not make a lot of sense:

The co-working company now says there=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Csubstantial doubt=
=E2=80=9D it will even be able to stay in business.
The New York-based company is bleeding cash, and customers of its office re=
ntals are canceling their memberships in droves, WeWork said in a statement=
 Tuesday. Its shares fell 26% in the first minutes of trading Wednesday mor=
ning.
WeWork=E2=80=99s stock has plunged 98% since the company went public in Oct=
ober 2021, wiping out nearly $9 billion in market value. The stock was trad=
ing at 16 cents early Wednesday. Its bonds are also at deeply distressed le=
vels. The company=E2=80=99s 7.875% unsecured notes due in 2025 last changed=
 hands for 33.5 cents on the dollar, according to data from Trace. =E2=80=
=A6
As the pandemic dragged on, WeWork insisted that the shift toward remote an=
d hybrid work would actually favor the company rather than weaken its busin=
ess. Employers would be more wary of signing long-term leases and would tur=
n to WeWork=E2=80=99s flexible models instead, the company argued.
Though that could still pan out, it hasn=E2=80=99t been happening quickly e=
nough for WeWork. In Tuesday=E2=80=99s statement, the company said more cus=
tomers were leaving and fewer new members were signing up than it had antic=
ipated. That churn was cutting into its occupancy rate, which dropped in th=
e second quarter compared to the previous one.

Ah, well. I have also  long=C2=A0been an admirer of WeWork founder Adam Neu=
mann=E2=80=99s ability to=C2=A0extract money from SoftBank,=C2=A0collecting=
=C2=A0hundreds of millions of dollars for himself at the peak and then walk=
ing away (for more money!) as WeWork crashed. As an=C2=A0entrepreneur, Neum=
ann is more impressive if the business he built is a lasting success, even =
at a lower valuation than the one he cashed out at. But as a=C2=A0trader, h=
is accomplishment is more impressive if the business goes to zero. =E2=80=
=9CSoftBank made a mistake that involved spending $10 billion to build a $4=
00 million company, and Adam Neumann was there to take the other side of th=
at mistake,=E2=80=9D I  once wrote, and that=C2=A0story is starker and shar=
per and more absurd if SoftBank spent the $10 billion on=C2=A0nothing.

 =20
   =20
      Yellow
   =20
 =20

Yellow Corp., the trucking company, shut down its operations in July and fi=
led for bankruptcy this past weekend. Its stock is up since it shut down op=
erations. That=E2=80=99s weird! Well, I mean, it=E2=80=99s weird, but it=E2=
=80=99s pretty common these days: Meme-stock companies sometimes become ext=
ra meme-y when they are near, or in, bankruptcy, as retail investors develo=
p conspiracy theories about short squeezes and rescue deals and rush to buy=
 the stock. And there have been some references to Yellow as a meme stock.
But that explanation does not quite work, because a lot of the buying in th=
e Yellow rally was done by an investment firm called MFN Partners that is a=
lso a big shareholder in another trucking company, and that disclosed a=C2=
=A042.5%=C2=A0stake in Yellow early last week. Not really the way meme inve=
sting works. What was going on? I  expressed some puzzlement earlier this w=
eek, but I suppose the simplest answer would be =E2=80=9CMFN knows trucking=
 and sees equity value here.=E2=80=9D Anyway:

Trucking company Yellow Corp's assets=C2=A0have attracted significant bidde=
rs and their sale could likely surpass the company's $1.4 billion in secure=
d debt, Fox Business reported on Tuesday, citing people with direct knowled=
ge of the matter.
That means stock holders will get a payday if significant unsecured debt cr=
editors do not emerge, Fox Business reporter Charles Gasparino said in a po=
st on X social media platform, formerly known as Twitter.
Shares of the company closed 24% higher in regular trading after the news. =
They fell 16% in extended trading.

I cannot stress enough that this is not investing advice and that you shoul=
d not go buy Yellow stock because I said it might get a recovery, but Charl=
ie Gasparino said it might anyway.
You could tell a simple corporate finance story in which bankruptcy, or rum=
ors of bankruptcy,=C2=A0should=C2=A0be good news for a declining company. T=
he story would go something like this:
=09Some companies are in decline; they have no good long-term prospects and=
 will eventually stop being viable and go bankrupt.=09Executives=C2=A0like=
=C2=A0running their company =E2=80=94=C2=A0they get paid, they like their c=
olleagues, running a company is prestigious =E2=80=94=C2=A0and are eternal =
optimists, so they will try to avoid bankruptcy as long as possible.=09Avoi=
ding bankruptcy as long as possible means spending cash on operations, losi=
ng money, gambling on redemption and not filing for bankruptcy=C2=A0until t=
here is negative equity value.=09Executives who are=C2=A0good=C2=A0stewards=
 of investor capital will try to liquidate their company=C2=A0early, when t=
he writing is on the wall rather than when all the value is gone. But that =
goes against the executives=E2=80=99 self-interest and self-confidence, and=
 so is rare.

And so=C2=A0if you see some declining company muddling along, you might ass=
ume =E2=80=9Cwell sure there=E2=80=99s value left here but they=E2=80=99re =
gonna waste it all, shareholders are never going to see a penny of it,=E2=
=80=9D and you might value the stock at roughly zero. And then if the compa=
ny said =E2=80=9Cokay never mind we=E2=80=99re going bankrupt and liquidati=
ng=E2=80=9D you might change your mind and buy the stock. That is not=C2=A0=
quite=C2=A0Yellow=E2=80=99s story =E2=80=94=C2=A0there were labor=C2=A0trou=
bles, etc. =E2=80=94 but it could be the right model. It is rare for compan=
ies to liquidate while there is still value left for shareholders, but it i=
s not impossible, and I suppose if you find one who is doing it you should =
bet on it.

