  [2] Not really. If you actually do destroy the value of your business, yo=
u can buy it back for $0 but it=E2=80=99s worth $0. Here, though, I suppose=
 it is crafty for Portnoy to be controversial in a way that thrills his fan=
s and alienates gaming regulators: That makes his business worth less *to P=
enn* (as a gambling brand), but more *to himself* (as a generator of media =
controversy).


  [3] Conceivably they should have asked for 99% of the proceeds, but I sup=
pose that they=E2=80=99re better off if he does have some incentive to sell=
 it and to maximize the price, so 50% is probably about right.


